Topics include friendship, mate choice, incest avoidance, cooperation, revenge, status, jealousy, emotions, group formation, and intergroup aggression.

ANTH 9
Click box to close.      
Full Title: Methods in the Human Behavioral Sciences
Description: Introduces the design and analysis of scientific studies on human behavior. Emphasizes theory-based testing of hypotheses, with examples drawn from human ecology, physiology, and behavior. Covers a range of quantitative and qualitative methods including observation, surveys, and experiments.
PreRequisite: ANTH 5 or 7 OR instructor approval
College: L&S
Units: 4.0
Grading: Optional
Textbook Information: http://www.ucsbstuff.com/SelectTermDept.aspx

Click box to close.      
Full Title: Basic Archaeological Concepts
Description: A survey of important archaeological methods of excavation, analysis, and interpretation. Focus will be on the problems and promise of various approaches to the explanation of past human behavior.
PreRequisite: Anthropology 3 or 3SS.
College: L&S
Units: 4.0

ANTH 103A
Click box to close.      
Full Title: Anthropology of China
Description: This course adopts an anthropological approach to contemporary China through ethnographic research. Topics include: Maoist society, rural life, migrant workers, gender and sexuality, media culture, youth culture, the urban work unit, from Maoist class-status system to capitalist class structure.
PreRequisite: upper division standing or instructor approval
College: L&S
Units: 4.0
Grading: Optional
Textbook Information: http://www.ucsbstuff.com/SelectTermDept.aspx

Full Title: Psychological Anthropology
Description: Field from Freud and Mead to present; how human nature (universal psychological mechanisms) and culture interact to form individual psychologies, identities, genders, social attitudes, worldviews, and traditions; how cognitive development shapes belief systems, reasoning and symbolism; emotions, preferences, thinking, and pathologies in cross- cultural perspective.

ANTH 129MG
Click box to close.      
Full Title: Behavioral Ecology of Hunter Gatherers
Description: A thorough introduction using a behavioral ecology approach to the diversity of behaviors found among foragers in Africa, South America, Southeast Asia, and Australia. Topics include: diet and subsistence, mating, demography, social behavior, mobility and settlement patterns, gender, indigenous rights, and conservation.
PreRequisite: Anthropology 5 or 7.
College: L&S
Units: 4.0
Grading: Optional

Full Title: Global Food Systems and Human Food Security
Description: Examines history of global food systems and its impacts on ecosystems, ecologies, and human nutrition and food security. How agricultural, capture fisheries, and aquacultural industries were integrated into the global food system. Provides information to make more informed decisions about consuming these products.
PreRequisite: Anthropology 2 or Environmental Studies 1 or 3.
College: L&S
Units: 4.0
Grading: Letter
